The soundtrack to the film was released on July 3, 2001 by [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music]].<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000009998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727084125/http://www.allmusic.com/album/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000009998 |archivedate=27 July 2013 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |last=Shurley |first=Neil |work= [[AllMusic]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> [[Elliot Goldenthal]] composed the entire score, as well as the film's theme song, "The Dream Within",<ref name=feature/> which had lyrics written by Richard Rudolf and vocals performed by [[Lara Fabian]].<ref name=tracksounds/> Director Hironobu Sakaguchi opted for the acclaimed Goldenthal instead of [[Nobuo Uematsu]], the composer of the ''Final Fantasy'' games' soundtracks, a decision met with mixed opinions as the former was completely unknown to many of the games' fans.<ref name="tracksounds">{{cite web |url=http://www.tracksounds.com/reviews/finalfantasy.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226151530/http://tracksounds.com/reviews/finalfantasy.htm |archivedate=26 December 2014 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within by Elliot Goldenthal |last=Coleman |first=Christopher |work= Tracksounds |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> The last song on the album and the second and final song to play during the film's credits (after "The Dream Within") is "[[Spirit Dreams Inside (Another Dream)|Spirit Dreams Inside]]" by Japanese rock band [[L'Arc-en-Ciel]].<ref name=tracksounds/>

The film's score was performed by the [[London Symphony Orchestra]]<ref name=feature/> with Belgian composer [[Dirk Brossé]] conducting. It was recorded in the United Kingdom at the [[Watford]] Coloseum and the London [[Associated Independent Recording|AIR]] Lyndhurst Hall and was mixed at the [[Manhattan Center]] Studios in the United States.<ref name="brosse">{{cite web | url = http://www.dirkbrosse.be/index.php/conductor/discography/category/conductor/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140224181745/http://www.dirkbrosse.be/index.php/conductor/discography/category/conductor/ |archivedate=24 February 2014 | title =Dirk Brosse discography | work =Dirk Brossé | accessdate = 23 December 2014}}</ref> In the liner notes to the album, Goldenthal describes the soundtrack as combining "orchestration techniques associated with the late 20th-century Polish [[Avant-garde music|avant-garde]], as well as my own experiments from ''[[Alien 3 (soundtrack)|Alien 3]]'', and 19th-century [[Richard Strauss|Straussian]] brass and string instrumentation."<ref name="liner">{{Cite AV media notes |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |year=2001 |first=Elliot |last=Goldenthal |author-link=Elliot Goldenthal |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[Sony Classical Records]] |id=SK 89697}}</ref> In the film's 'Making of' featurette, Goldenthal states he used "ghostly [[choir|choral]]" music when the Phantoms are emerging, in an attempt to give a celestial feeling, and focused on low [[Brass instrument|brass]] clusters and [[taiko]] drum rhythms for violent scenes. When Aki talks about a dying girl, Goldenthal used a piano in order to give a domestic home-like feeling to a completely foreign environment, also choosing to use a flute each time Aki focusses on Gaia, as he believed it to be the most "human kind of instrument".<ref name=feature/>

The album was met with positive reviews. Neil Shurley from [[AllMusic]], who gave the album 4 out of 5, stated the album would probably have been nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] if the film itself had been more popular,<ref name="allmusic"/> as did the reviewer from Soundtrack Express, who gave the soundtrack 5 out of 5.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundtrack-express.com/osts/finalfantasy.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818030515/http://www.soundtrack-express.com/osts/finalfantasy.htm |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within |work=Soundtrack Express |archivedate=18 August 2009 | deadurl=yes |accessdate=3 February 2010}}</ref> Christopher Coleman from Tracksounds gave the soundtrack 10 out of 10, stating the feel of the album was "expansive and majestic" and that the score elevated the viewing experience of the film.<ref name=tracksounds/> A review from ''Filmtracks'' gave the album 4 out of 5, calling it "an easy album to recommend", adding "parts of it will blow you out of your seat."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/final_fantasy.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710152931/http://filmtracks.com/titles/final_fantasy.html |archivedate=10 July 2014 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within |date=29 June 2001 |work=Filmtracks |accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> Dan Goldwasser from Soundtrack.net also gave the soundtrack 4 out of 5, calling it a "must have".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundtrack.net/album/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710152931/http://filmtracks.com/titles/final_fantasy.html |archivedate=10 July 2014 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within |last=Goldwasser |first=Dan |date=21 June 2004 |work= Soundtrack.net|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>
{{Listen|filename=Elliot Goldenthal - Final Fantasy - The Phantom Plains.ogg|title="The Phantom Plains"|description=Sample of "The Phantom Plains" from the soundtrack album.|format=[[Ogg]]|pos=left}}

The album peaked at No. 19 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s Top Soundtracks list and No. 193 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] on July 28, 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000009998/awards |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128132753/http://www.allmusic.com/album/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000009998/awards |archivedate=28 January 2015 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within: Awards |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> The track "The Dream Within" was nominated for "Best Original Song Written for a Film" at the 2002 [[World Soundtrack Academy|World Soundtrack Awards]], but lost to "[[If I Didn't Have You (Disney song)|If I Didn't Have You]]" which was composed for ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsoundtrackawards.com/en/awards/c/best-original-song-written-directly-for-a-film/8 |title=Best Original Song Written directly for a Film |work=[[World Soundtrack Academy]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>
{{Clear}}

==Release==

===Box office===
Before the film's release, there was already skepticism of its potential to be financially successful. Chris Taylor from [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] magazine noted that video game adaptations had a poor track record at the box office and that it was Sakaguchi's first feature film.<ref name="time" />  The film debuted on July 2, 2001 at the Mann Bruins Theater in Los Angeles, California,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seeing-stars.com/Meet/MoviePremierePressReleases/FinalFantasy.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110001333/http://www.seeing-stars.com/Meet/MoviePremierePressReleases/FinalFantasy.shtml |archivedate=10 November 2014 |title=Advisory/The World Premiere of Columbia Pictures & Square Pictures' "Final Fantasy" |date=28 June 2001 |work=Seeing Stars |accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> and was released in the United States on July 11, making $32 million in North America and going on to gross $85 million in worldwide box office receipts.<ref name="Boxofficemojo"/> The film achieved average to poor results at the box office in most of Southeast Asia; however, it performed well in Australia, New Zealand and South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2001/film/news/b-o-s-animal-planet-1117850492/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128133501/http://variety.com/2001/film/news/b-o-s-animal-planet-1117850492/ |archivedate=28 January 2015 |title=B.O.'s animal planet |last=Groves |first=Don |date=30 July 2001 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> In 2006 [[Boston.com]] regarded it as the 4th [[List of box office bombs|biggest box office bomb]], estimating the film's losses at the end of its cinema run at over $94 million.<ref name=bomb/> In March 2012 [[CNBC]] considered it to be the 9th biggest box office bomb,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/38815985/page/9 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130141100/http://www.cnbc.com/id/38815985/page/9 |archivedate=30 January 2015 |title=The 15 Biggest Box Office Bombs |last=Bukszpan |first=Daniel |date=20 March 2012 |work=[[CNBC]] |accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> though ''Time''{{'}}s list of the ten biggest box office failures, which was released on the same day, did not include the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://business.time.com/2012/03/21/the-top-ten-biggest-money-losing-movies-of-all-time/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025015440/http://business.time.com/2012/03/21/the-top-ten-biggest-money-losing-movies-of-all-time/ |archivedate=25 October 2014 |title=The Top 10 Biggest Money-Losing Movies of All Time |last=Matthews |first=Christopher |date=20 March 2012 |work=[[CNBC]] |accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>
{{quote box|width=30%|quote=If the ambitious mix of East–West, movie-game and anime-action doesn't pay off, we may still remember this as the moment true CG actors were born.|source=''Time'' magazine<ref name="time" />}}

===Critical reception===
The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported an approval rating of 45% based on 146 reviews, with an average rating of 5.3/10. The website's critical consensus reads, "The movie raises the bar for computer animated movies, but the story is dull and emotionally removed."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/final_fantasy_the_spirits_within/ |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within (2001) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a [[weighted average]], assigned a score of 49 out of 100 based on 28 critics, indicating "mixed or average reviews".<ref name="Metacritic">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within Reviews |accessdate=December 23, 2014 |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60fg8oU5G?url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within |archivedate=August 3, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>

[[Roger Ebert]] was a strong advocate of the film; he gave it 3½ stars out of four, praising it as a "technical milestone" while conceding that its "nuts and bolts" story lacked "the intelligence and daring of, say, [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[A.I. Artificial Intelligence|A.I.]]''" He noted that while he did not once feel convinced Aki Ross was an actual human being, she was "lifelike", stating her creators "dare us to admire their craft. If Aki is not as real as a human actress, she's about as human as a [[Playboy Playmate|Playmate]] who has been retouched to glossy perfection."{{sfn|Ebert|2003|page=216}} He also expressed a desire for the film to succeed in hopes of seeing more films made in its image, though he was skeptical of its ability to be accepted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within-2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141013094437/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/final-fantasy-the-spirits-within-2001 |archivedate=13 October 2014 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within (PG-13) |last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |date=11 July 2001 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] gave a more negative review, stating that while the animation was brilliant, the "solemnly realist human faces look shriekingly phoney precisely because they're almost there but not quite", concluding "The story is adequate, if familiar, but after half an hour relapses into cliche."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/aug/03/culture.reviews1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509215207/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/aug/03/culture.reviews1 |archivedate=9 May 2014 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within |last=Bradshaw |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Bradshaw |date=3 August 2001 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>

===Reception of Aki Ross===
[[File:Ffmaxim aki ross.jpg|upright|thumb|left|''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]''{{'}}s featuring of Aki in their "Hot 100" list resulted in increased media attention towards the character. | alt=Aki Ross in a bikini, as featured in Maxim magazine]]
Aki's appearance was received positively by critics,<ref>{{cite news |last=Gumbel |first=Andrew |title=Hollywood finds the perfect star: Tall, attractive, and guaranteed not to strike |work=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=21 May 2001 |page=3}}</ref> with praise for the finer details of the character model such as the rendering of her hair.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/review/film/s350149.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216070609/http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/review/film/s350149.htm |archivedate=16 December 2013 |title=Final Fantasy: The Spirit's Within |accessdate=23 December 2014 |last=Spencer |first=Megan |work=[[Triple J]] }}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly'' named Aki an "[[it girl]]", stating that "Calling this action heroine a cartoon would be like calling a [[Rembrandt]] a doodle."<ref>{{cite web| title=The It List 2001;Aki | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/itlist/2001/7.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010625105611/http://www.ew.com/ew/itlist/2001/7.html | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | archivedate=25 June 2001 | accessdate= 15 January 2015}}</ref> She was voted one of the sexiest women of 2001 by ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' and its readers, ranking at No. 87 out of 100, becoming the first fictional woman to ever make the list, additionally appearing on the issue's cover in a purple bikini.<ref name="nyt">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/06/style/perfect-model-gorgeous-no-complaints-made-of-pixels.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113060830/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/06/style/perfect-model-gorgeous-no-complaints-made-of-pixels.html |archivedate=13 November 2013 |title=Perfect Model: Gorgeous, No Complaints, Made of Pixels |accessdate=23 December 2014 |last=La Ferda |first=Ruth |date=6 May 2001 |pages=1–2 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The same image appeared in the "Babes: The Girls of Sci Fi" special issue of ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |year=2002 |title=Aki Ross |journal=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]] |issue=Babes: The Girls of Sci Fi |pages=55}}</ref> Ruth La Ferla from ''[[The New York Times]]'' described her as having the "sinewy efficiency" of ''[[Alien (franchise)|Alien]]'' franchise character [[Ellen Ripley]] and visual appeal of [[Julia Roberts]]' portrayal of [[Erin Brockovich]].<ref name="nyt"/> The book ''Digital Shock: Confronting the New Reality'' by Herve Fischer described her as a virtual actress having a "beauty that is 'really' impressive", comparing her to video game character [[Lara Croft]].{{sfn|Fischer|2006|page=96}} In contrast, Livia Monnet criticized her character as an example of the constantly kidnapped female in Japanese cinema, further "diluted" by her existence solely as a computer-generated character representing "an ideal, cinematic female character that has no real referent."{{sfn|Bolton|2007}} Writing in the book ''Action and Adventure Cinema'', Marc O'Day described her as among the "least overtly eroticised" female characters in science fiction, though stated that Aki was "transformed in a variety of poses into an erotic fantasy machine" in a photo shoot that was included on the DVD's special features.{{sfn|O'Day|2004|page=350}}

===Legacy and related media===
The merger between [[Square Co.|Square]] and [[Enix]], which had been under consideration since at least 2000 according to [[Yasuhiro Fukushima]], Enix chairman at the time, was delayed because of the failure of the film and Enix' hesitation at merging with a company that had just lost a substantial amount of money.<ref>{{cite web |last=Long |first=Andrew |year=2003 | work=RPGamer | url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q2-2003/042503e.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113044027/http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q2-2003/042503e.html |archivedate=13 November 2014 | title= Square-Enix Gives Chrono Break Trademark Some Playmates | accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> Square Pictures announced in late January 2002 that they were closing down, largely due to the commercial failure of ''The Spirits Within''.<ref name=briscoe /> The film's CGI effects have been compared favourably with later CGI films such as [[James Cameron]]'s 2009 film ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Child |first=Ben |title=Avatar: a first look at the trailer for James Cameron's 3D spectacular |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2009/aug/21/avatar-first-trailer-james-cameron-3d |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303011340/http://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2009/aug/21/avatar-first-trailer-james-cameron-3d |archivedate=3 March 2014 |date=21 August 2009 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Usher |first=William |title=AMD Says Xbox 720 Will Have Avatar Quality Graphics |date=17 July 2011 |url=http://www.cinemablend.com/games/AMD-Says-Xbox-720-Have-Avatar-Quality-Graphics-33537.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224235928/http://www.cinemablend.com/games/AMD-Says-Xbox-720-Have-Avatar-Quality-Graphics-33537.html |archivedate=24 February 2014 |work=Cinema Blend |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>  In 2011, [[BioWare]] art director Derek Watts cited ''The Spirits Within'' as a major influence on the successful ''[[Mass Effect]]'' series of [[action role-playing game]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hussain|first=Tamoor|title=BioWare: Mass Effect inspired 'a lot' by Final Fantasy film: Art director discusses "great" influences |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/309198/bioware-mass-effect-inspired-a-lot-by-final-fantasy-film/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228010247/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/309198/bioware-mass-effect-inspired-a-lot-by-final-fantasy-film/ |archivedate=28 December 2014 |work=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=27 June 2011 |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> In the first episode of the Square Enix published 2015 video game ''[[Life Is Strange]]'', when the lead interacts with a TV, she mentions the idea of watching the film, and says "I don't care what anybody says, that's one of the best sci-fi films ever made."<ref>{{cite video game|title=Life Is Strange|developer=Dontnod Entertainment|publisher=Square Enix|date=30 January 2015|platform=Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, Xbox One, Xbox 360|level=Chrysalis}}</ref> Although the film was loosely based on a video game series, there were never any plans for a game adaptation of the film itself. Sakaguchi indicated the reason for this was the lack of powerful gaming hardware at the time, feeling the graphics in any game adaptation would be far too much of a step down from the graphics in the film itself.<ref name=dream/> A novelization was written by [[Dean Wesley Smith]] and published by ''[[Pocket Books]]'' in June 2001.{{sfn|Smith|2001}} ''The Making of Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within'', a companion book, was published by ''[[Dorling Kindersley#BradyGames|BradyGames]]'' in August 2001.{{sfn|Kent|2001}} Edited by [[Steven L. Kent]], the 240 page color book contains a foreword by director Sakaguchi and extensive information on all aspects of the film's creation, including concept art, storyboards, sets and props, layout, motion capture and animation, as well as a draft of the full [[Screenplay|script]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesfirst.com/reviews/monica/ff_swbook/ff_swbook.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229155156/http://www.gamesfirst.com/reviews/monica/ff_swbook/ff_swbook.htm |archivedate=29 February 2012 |title=The Making of Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within |last=Hafer |first=Monica |date=10 September 2001 |work=GamesFirst! |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>

===Accolades===
The film won the "Jury Prize" at the 2002 [[Japan Media Arts Festival]].{{sfn|Bolton|2007}} It was nominated for "Best Sound Editing – Animated Feature Film, Domestic and Foreign" at the 49th [[Motion Picture Sound Editors#Golden Reel Awards|Golden Reel Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2002/film/news/sound-editors-tap-noms-for-golden-reel-awards-1117860492/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128135308/http://variety.com/2002/film/news/sound-editors-tap-noms-for-golden-reel-awards-1117860492/ |archivedate=28 January 2015 |title=Sound editors tap noms for Golden Reel Awards |last=Hobbs |first=John |date=10 February 2002 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> as well as "[[Online Film Critics Society Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Feature]]" at the 5th [[Online Film Critics Society]] awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ofcs.org/awards/2001-awards-5th-annual/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007094055/http://www.ofcs.org/awards/2001-awards-5th-annual/ |archivedate=7 October 2014 |title=2001 Awards (5th Annual) |work= [[Online Film Critics Society]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> The film's trailer was nominated for the "Golden Fleece" award at the 3rd [[Golden Trailer Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goldentrailer.com/awards.gta3.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307155929/http://www.goldentrailer.com/awards.gta3.php |archivedate=7 March 2012 |title=Winners and Nominees for the 3rd Annual Golden Trailer Awards |work=[[Golden Trailer Awards]] |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>
